posts.com:
/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

Since people are complaining and I thought about this question that I thought was interesting (plus I've seen people ask other questions periodically throughout threads anyway)

>your type
>what fear response(s) do you typically resort to (afaik there are 4 (perhaps more, idk) - fight, flight, freeze, and fawn. I've also heard it said that giving up/shutting down can also be a fear response.)
I don't know if fear responses really line up with personality at all but mine kind of did so I thought this would be a good question potentially

ISFJ
I usually freeze or become very quiet both when I'm alerted to a possible threat and when I am aware that there is one, though I also inch toward "fight". I don't like having my back toward people or things that make me feel unsafe even to run away, so I don't run even though I'm a bit of a coward. Part of it also probably due to paralysis caused by indecision.
In some cases I very much have what feels like a primal urge to sucker punch a person because of how anxious and unsafe they are making me feel, but that's frowned upon unfortunately.

>>72113962
I didn't see your questions til I wrote up mine so I will at least answer yours.

>favorite shower temperature
I like it warm to cold, but I get anxiety about something bad happening like being attacked in the shower like a horror movie, or the police busting the door down and making me get out of the shower naked. The hot water relaxes me enough to keep those thoughts away.
>what are you doing to better your self?
Trying to accept that I am different from others but that I still have some worth. It's harder some days than others. I find it hard to relate to others and yet I am most inspired by others. I suppose I am a pioneer in a weird way. I hope one day I can make something of myself and show others that may be like me that it's possible.

>Not just mundane, but also over-complicated where it's not necessary
>It's pointed out it's not easily falsifiable in its principles
I think many researchers don't understand it properly, as Friston himself said:
> "the free energy principle is what it is - a principle. Like Hamilton's principle of stationary action, it cannot be falsified. It cannot be disproven. In fact, there's not much you can do with it, unless you ask whether measurable systems conform to the principle."
In other words, like entropy, it isn't really "scientific," but more like a metaphysical principle, and thus a transcendental illusion rather than a ground truth about reality. Hence why I said I don't fully adhere to it - it doesn't give any ultimate truth, but helps understand a certain mode of life and way of representing the world. To the original point, in relation to sensing; yes you sense the world, but is it just "you" that senses, in a merely passive manner? Or is there something else, of very different origins, that inscribes how this process is to take place within you? You also think and feel, but is it truly your thinking and feeling? I don't claim to have answers, but it's fun to look at things differently! I think it's bad for the mind to be trapped.

I believe everything has consequences, even if you act by principles. That said, I try to find a balance between the two. Of course, I think a lot about the consequences of my actions, but it's also important that my decisions are mine and not someone else's.

I'd rather strive for a sensible stance which incorporates a bit of each.

OK I just wrote another really long post to add on to this OP but it ended up being me just speedily venting about my childhood specifics so I deleted it even though I wanted to post it.

In short, I wanted to answer your question by saying I was damaged as a kid, and I developed a neurotic obsession with philosophical and existential concerns since a young age. Recently, I came to the decision to paradoxically commit to a non-commital nihilism, and to stop, for the time being, explicitly looking through the shards of my life for some greater meaning, and just accept it as it is.

Doing this has given me some new perspectives on myself. I realized that I am a damaged person, and that at a young age I lost the ability to feel everyday joy that drives most normal people forward. I have felt empty and dead inside for years. Upon realizing this, I was able to feel something genuine for the first time in a long time.

Though, before in all my emptiness and languor, I did find one thing that could make me feel: great beauty. In all things, but it is mostly forms of serious art that does it for me. That kind of great, profound understanding of beauty that brings people to their knees is the only thing powerful enough to bring me any joy, because of my personal problems. And so, I have realized that pursuing that beauty is what I must do with my life.

My main squeeze for this has been literature. So now I have decided to pursue the written word, and try to write. I also am pursuing mathematics in school for the pursuit of that same profound beauty.

So, OP, to answer your question in a very roundabout and stimulant-induced way, my plan (which has worked so far) is to use stimulants in order to control my gloom and emptiness, so that I can pursue these moments of joy and beauty, since they are the only thing powerful enough to make me feel.

It's not a contamination per say, more like an irrational fear of immorality. Something I ask ask myself obsessively everyday is "Are you a good person?"
Now, I am aware that there is no such thing as the ultimate good person, morality isn't black and white, there's a lot of gray area. But despite knowing this and being self-aware of it, I still have all of these fears and intrusive thoughts about it. I begin to really hate myself when I start thinking about what a bad person I am and how I can never truly be a good person. But instead of accepting that, I start to think what IF I can be a good person after all? Maybe I should try a little harder, be a little better. Even though I have been told that I'm a nice person and I know for sure I put a conscious effort into being one, my brain says that it simply is not enough. There has to be more I can do, there just has to. And it isn't always about actions I do but thoughts I have. If I think negatively about someone even briefly, I will feel guilt almost immediately and hyper-focus on it. If I read manga where the main character dies and I enjoyed the story, I will mistake that as me enjoying his demise, thus making me a horrible person. If I kill a fly, I'll feel extreme sadness and remorse. If I even thought about killing said fly, then I will feel guilt. I'm sure you get the picture. OCD is all about irrationality and uncertainty.
I'm not a master of it, but I am learning to deal with my scrupulosity and I think I can handle it well most of the time. There's days where it just gets the best of me however. Sorry for the wait and for the long reply!
